Well there went an hour and twenty minutes of my life I'll never get back. My wife and I love animated movies and with the almost 5 star reviews we thought this would be a good movie to watch. WRONG! I guess if you're a toddler or a child that would be in to Barney or Teletubbies this would be a good movie for them. I should have read some of the reviews instead of just going by the rating. One reviewer said that there was "mild violence" and another said there was bullying and too many fart jokes in it. WOW! I thought that the Mellinial's were a "Special" generation, I'm afraid to see how "Special" these 3 to 14 year olds turn out after some of the reviewers raising them say they think there's too much mild violence, bullying and fart jokes in this movie. Hopfully there is a safe place in their homes so their special little snowflakes can get away from all of the carnage that's in this movie. And to say that if you like the Ice Age movies that this movie is similar is way off base. The Ice Age movies are good and my wife and I enjoy them. This flick is for children under 7 or their guardians that want to keep little Susie and Johnny sheltered and away from this cruel, crude, and vile existence most of us call life and sad reality.

I thought this was an awesome kids movie! I'm actually a mother but found myself caught up in the tale and surprised at every turn.  The details of the flood were definitely toned down so you don't have to worry about young children being upset. No one actually dies in the film. Also, Noah is only mentioned; not seen.
The ending made so much sense to me and portrayed how God has a purpose for everything...that was for the animals rejected...found their true reason for existing.
Really it was such a sweet movie that encourages team work, friendship, and as I said above, trusting God and his plan for you.

My friends and I watched this movie at four in the morning. I expected something bad, but nothing to this degree. It starts off seeming just like a generic kids movie, but then devolves slowly into a horror show that caused one of my friends to bleed from his eyes. The movie sells itself as being about Noah's ark, but we never see Noah and there are no religious undertones what so ever. I am not religious, but still feel deeply cheated. The main characters are also the most annoying creatures imaginable and I was actually rooting for the lion when he kicked them off the ark. Their annoyingness peaks when Finny creates a boat that would've prevented all the plights of the movie, but then loses it just because he wasn't holding onto the rope. This scene was so painful I cried out in agony upon seeing it.

Things eventually reach a point of no return when there is a sequence in which rocks fall like Tetris and disappear and then crush someone. This was so not funny that I have not had a sense of humor since viewing it. This horrific scene was then followed by a blob creature using some wooden sticks to glide somehow to safety. It is at this point that the movie's logic and rules began to collapse in upon themselves and it is no longer savable. After a series of nauseating, illogical scenes with no actual antagonist other than mentally handicapped bats that are being called Gryphons we come to the mind bendingly awful ending.

When Finny is about to get to the ark, he is knocked into the water, his dad then dives after him while the Grymps watch. The dad holds Finny, assuming he's dead for some reason and making no attempt to bring him to the surface, then suddenly they realize they've been aquatic creatures the whole time and just forgot somehow, meaning the entire movie's plot was pointless. There is also no explanation on why or how they forgot they were aquatic creatures. As if this scene was not bad enough, suddenly the bats that are called Gryphons show back up and dive in after Finny. They chase Finny through underwater caves, and for some unknown reason do not need oxygen and can speak underwater without inhaling water and dying. You would think this would be the end of the maddening stupidity, but it is not. Suddenly the gliding blob creature returns to save the day and it turns out he was just a whale the whole time, using the exact same plot device the Nesterians did. Once again it is not explained how on Earth he forgot he was a whale.

They then all go into the water to have fun or something, other than the Grymps who are now on the ark even though seemingly the plot of the movie was all the creatures that we know of now were the only ones that made it onto the ark, and that was the point of having the Gryphons die and the Nesterians go into the water, proposing they're deep sea creatures and that's why they're not known, they also make a point to show the Tanglefoot now getting onto the ark, yet the Grymps get on the boat and everything is fine. So that entire theme was meaningless. Upon finishing it it felt as if I had lost a good portion of my brain cells, whereas my friend just seemed to be in an agonized delirium.

I would strongly suggest never showing your child this movie if you had any kind of respect for their intellect or judgement. If you want to show your children a reasonable religiously themed movie I would show them At Jesus's Side.

In the event that you never heard of All Creatures Big and Small; theres a good possibility thats because this film goes by a lot of different names.  Sometimes it depends on where you happen to be in the world.  Other times even that doesnt seem to matter.  Its also known as Ooops! Noah is Gone, other times its titled Two by Two, and even at times Ooops the Ark has Gone.  Regardless of what the cover says, all these titles lead back to the 2015 German-Belgian-Luxembourg-Irish 3D computer-animated adventure that takes the classic Biblical tale of Noahs Ark and tells it with a comedic twist from the perspective of the animals involved.

In theme and delivery, the piece feels a bit like the Ice Age series from Blue Sky- with the antics of small fuzzy animals playing against the contrast of larger more underlying themes of doom and extinction.  However, while the Ice Ages seem to rely heavily upon slapstick and visual humor, All Creatures Big and Small contains a surprising deal of layered humor.  Kids will laugh at the visual gags, complete with cuddly main characters and some beautifully done action sequences but adults tuning in may find a bit to enjoy as well; especially by the end when the film manages to tie up some potential loose ends brilliantly.

The story centers on a pair of nestrians, a partially fictitious species of animal (rumored to have been inspired by a very real rare aquatic sea slug called Glaucus Atlanticus) who are summoned to report to a meeting concerning all the animals of the world.  There they receive word that am impending flood approaches and only those animals selected for passage upon the ark stand a chance for salvation.  It should be noted that not unlike staple entries to the genre from Pixar A Bugs Life and Cars, not a single human makes an appearance in this film.  Noah, in fact, is referenced only by name.

Discovering that they are not on the invite-only list for Ark passage, father nestrian Dave disguises he and son Finny to look like grymps; small solitary cat-like creatures that do indeed make the grade for board-age.  Should be a simple cruise until the floodwaters retreat except for one minor snag:  young nestrian, Finny, and the young grymp, Leah, soon find themselves outside the Arks deck when the flood arrives.  From here the film focuses on Finny and Leahs attempts to survive the rising waters in hopes that the Ark will come back for them while their parents do everything they can to convince the ships animal crew to turn the vessel around for their children.

The visuals and animation cycles here are fantastic with a nice vivid color pallet, crisp editing and character models that manage to look remarkably similar to the real-life animals they are replicating without ever losing the cartoony base.  Critics the world over seem to find fault with the look of the film but its clear many of them have never worked in animation or the CG medium.  Textures of fur and plant, water and droplets are all first-rate here from the first frame to the last.  Lighting too is spot on- and some of the luminescence effects under water give up nothing to Pixars much celebrated firefly effect from The Good Dinosaur.

Pacing too is excellent with neither scenes that drag on unnecessarily long nor moments that feel as if they were added as filler to hit the correct run-time.  Rather, every single sequence in the film comes off as a catalyst to advance the story.

Voice acting is also delightful- many of the jokes work off the dynamic of character interaction and the cast of actors here show seasoning and excellent timing as almost all of the humor contained within hits its mark.

Its not entirely clear to me why the film manages to receive as many poor reviews from critics as it does.  Regardless of whether viewing it for its technical merit, narrative, originality or entertainment value, the piece does a lot of things right.

The core themes of friendship sprouting up from unlikely duos, the awe-demanding power of nature, and even the absolutely brilliant reason not all animals were selected to board proves that no part of the screenplay was left to chance.

This is one of those rare moments where my best advice would be to ignore the critics, skeptics haters and naysayers and give this one a chance.  Just remember you may have to do a little research first to find out what its called in your area.

I'm a second grade teacher, and my school district cut our access to Netflix. They haven't blocked Amazon Video yet!!  I needed a rainy day recess movie, and stumbled upon All Creatures. I had never heard of it, but I needed something rated G! Well, the kids loved it within minutes of starting the movie.  I know this because they were silent!  I settled into grading papers until my ears pricked up when I heard "ark" and "Noah".  I let them keep watching wondering if it was going to have a obvious Christian message, which wouldn't have been wasted on the class I have this year but would not be appropriate in my public school classroom. Other than referencing the flood, the ark, and Noah, the move was fine for my public school class. They loved it. We watched half of it for recess that day. The next rainy day, students begged to watch the other half for indoor recess.

Although it won't win an Oscar and it isn't, exactly, the way it happens in the Bible either (or even close).  Other than the presence of The Ark, the mere mention of a man named Noah who built it, a flood to wipe out everything and lots of pairs of animals (Apparently, in this story, it would appear there is no requirement for the male and female of the species to board.. Hmm)  One might be insulted there is no mention of God in this story... but one might also be relieved they didn't insult God or Noah either, in the telling of it. (Unlike the way another movie about Noah, which came out recently, did)  BUT... That being said...

This is highly entertaining, good clean fun and just ADORABLE, with a capital "A".  There are also a few important life lessons to be learned from its message... among them: laying one's life down for another, teamwork, friendship, the power of a hug, to obey one's parents, acceptance of those who look a little different from yourself, appreciating other's talents... all these things and more, I am certain God would approve of.  I say, click 'play' and do just that... Play.

While in the description of this movie it says that it is about Noah's ark and flood, you never see Noah, his family, or anything biblical in this movie.  Well except the animals, ark, and flood.  So, it's not a Christian movie but it is family friendly.  The graphics and storyline are great.  Okay, now that that's out of the way, if you or your little ones love Ice Age Movies, then you/they will love this.  The main characters are father and son who are banned from getting into the ark.  They know that there will be a worldwide destructive flood so they do their best to get into the ark.  They run into some enemies and friends in their quest to be safe.  I really enjoyed this movie and so did my daughter (7), nephews (5 and 9).
